7025f070-92c0-4b18-b59e-1adb383dc926.11e99da9-3955-477f-9bd5-842cd70db978.description=
Adds a flow variable into the local context (available to itself and child flows only)

Input Parameters\:
keyName - the name of the flow variable to use
myValue - the value to assign the flow variable

Responses\:
success - assigned the flow variable

Scriptlet Example\:
[$scriptletContext putGlobal\: $keyName, $myValue];
7025f070-92c0-4b18-b59e-1adb383dc926.a645a0d3-95ba-47bd-8eb7-ebdf78e85872.description=
Takes a reference to XML (in the form of a String) and the specified XPath Query is run against the XML and returns the results in a form of a delimited list. The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) organization provides the XPath specification (http\://www.w3.org).

Inputs\:
xml - The XML (in the form of a String)

xpathQuery - The XPath Query that is wanted to be run. See Examples in Notes section below.

delimiter- The delimiter used to separate values in the returnResult list. 

Default value\: ,

Result Value\:
returnResult - The result of the operation. If multiple XPaths are defined then this will add the delimiter between each value. There is no final delimiter.

Notes\:
Examples\:
The XPath Query can be specified as a single query in a format similiar to the following\:
/employees/employee[@id\="3"]/*[name()\="name" or name()\="jobDescription" or name()\="salary" or name()\="managerId"]/text()

This would return the following results\:
Goofy,tester,$50,1

Or if more then one XPath query needs to be specified, populate xpathQuery using the XPath concat function.  As an example here is sample of a xpathQuery value using XPath concat function\:
concat(/employees/employee[@id\="2"]/name/text(),',',/employees/employee[@id\="2"]/jobDescription/text(),',',/employees/employee[@id\="2"]/managerId/text(),',',/employees/employee[@id\="2"]/salary/text())

The output using the concat xpathQuery input would return the following results\:
Donald Duck,Lead Coder,1,$50

The examples above use the following xml string value\:


  
    Mickey Mouse
    Chief
    $100
    
  
  
    Donald Duck
    Lead Coder
    $50
    1
  
  
    Goofy
    tester
    $50
    1
  
  
    Pluto
    Coder - grade 1
    $25
    2
7025f070-92c0-4b18-b59e-1adb383dc926.acae215f-c87f-49af-a601-3492895655e2.description=
Invokes web service methods.  This operation should not be used directly\!  Please use the wizard to build flows that use this operation.

Inputs\:
xmlTemplate - The template of the soap request to make.
inputMap - A map used to map between template names and user-friendly names. The tamplate names are pipe-delimited xpaths of the xmltemplate location, with a numerical element for lists.
url - The url to post to. 
header_SOAPAction - The SOAPAction http header field, defined by many web services for indicating the intent of the request
wswAuthenticationType - The authentication type to use for the username and password input. http is default (Uses http authentication), other options are 'ws-security digest' and 'ws-security text' WARNING\: ws-security text transmits passwords in clear-text
WSSecuritySignRequest - true or false, should the SOAP request be signed using WS-Security.
WSSecurityEncryptRequest - true or false, should the entire SOAP request be signed using WS-Security
WSSecurityTimestampRequest - true or false, should the Timestamp attribute be added to the WS-Security header
WSSecurityKeystore - keystore to use for encrypting and signing requests.
WSSecurityKeystoreType - The type of WSSecurityKeystore.
WSSecurityKeystorePassword - The password for WSSecurityKeystore.
contentType - Value to be used in the Content-Type http header
username - The username to use for authenticating with the web service
password - The password to use for authenticating with the web service
trustAllRoots - Enables weak security over SSL. A SSH certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it. valid options are\: true/false.
useCookies - Enables cookie tracking. Cookies will be stored between consecutive calls. valid options are\: true/false.
timeout - a timeout after which the connection should be terminated, or 0 for no timeout.
proxy - A proxy to use when accessing the web service.
proxyPort - A port on the proxy to connect to.
proxyUsername - A username to use when connecting to the proxy.
proxyPassword - A password to use when connecting to the proxy.
keystore - the path to the keystore to use for SSL Client Certificates when using http authentication
keystorePassword - the password for the keystore when using http authentication
ICONCLUDE_WSW_VERSION - This value is used internally by the operation

Any additional inputs that follow these are added by the Web Service Wizard, and they are specific to the particular web service method being called.

Responses\:
success - SOAP request completed successfully.
failure - something went wrong.

Returns\:
document - raw XML response
documentStripped - raw XML response stripped of namespaces for ease in parsing with XML XPath operations

Notes\:
If you add new step-level inputs with the name header_, where  is the name of an html header, then that html header will be set to the given value in the HTTP request.
7025f070-92c0-4b18-b59e-1adb383dc926.description=
This subflow was created by the Web Services Wizard to invoke the search operation on file\:/C\:/Users/andy.roth/Desktop/hpoo.wsdl. Note that the inputs to this flow which correspond to web service inputs are optional inputs.  This is due to the fact that web services definitions usually incorrectly indicate that too many inputs are required, and mirroring those settings in the flow would force you to enter unused values when running the flow.  The xmlTemplate input on the Invoke Method 2 step of this flow contains a template of the xml message to be sent, and the fields preceded by the comment "<\!--Optional\:-->" or "<\!--zero or more repetitions-->" are those which the web service indicates are optional; all others are indicated to be required.

Inputs\:
    webserviceHost - The host that is running the web service
    webservicePort - The port on the host running the web service
    basePath - The input named search|basePath of the complex type\: search
    queryString - The input named search|queryString of the complex type\: search

Results\:
    document - The raw XML response of the web service
    documentStripped - The XML response of the web service stripped of namespaces
    searchReturn - The output given by the XPath\: /Envelope/Body/searchResponse/searchReturn/text()

Responses\:
    success - The SOAP command was accepted by the web service
    failure - Something went wrong while making the SOAP request
